Worksheet 1

Problem 3

Let V=F[x1,…,xn]V = \F\br{x_1, \ldots, x_n}V=F[x1​,…,xn​] be the space of polynomials in nnn-variables. A polynomial f∈Vf \in Vf∈V is said to be homogeneous of degree kkk if the degree (i.e. the sum of the exponents) of each non-zero term of fff is kkk. A polynomial f∈Vf \in Vf∈V is said to be symmetric if exchanging any two variables yields the same polynomial, namely f(x1,…,xi,…xj,…,xn)=f(x1,…,xj,…,xi,…,xn)f\p{x_1, \ldots, x_i, \ldots x_j, \ldots, x_n} = f\p{x_1, \ldots, x_j, \ldots, x_i, \ldots, x_n}f(x1​,…,xi​,…xj​,…,xn​)=f(x1​,…,xj​,…,xi​,…,xn​) for all i,j∈{1,…,n}i, j \in \set{1, \ldots, n}i,j∈{1,…,n}.

  1. Prove that VVV is a vector space.
  2. Prove that the space of homogeneous degree kkk polynomials form a subspace of VVV.
  3. Prove that the space of symmetric polynomials in nnn variables is a subspace of VVV.
Solution.

First, note that addition and scalar multiplication are defined as follows. Let

f=∑i1,i2…,in=0∞ai1i2⋯inx1i1⋯xnin,g=∑i1,i2…,in=0∞bi1i2⋯inx1i1⋯xnin, f = \sum_{i_1,i_2\ldots,i_n=0}^\infty a_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n} x_1^{i_1} \cdots x_n^{i_n}, \quad g = \sum_{i_1,i_2\ldots,i_n=0}^\infty b_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n} x_1^{i_1} \cdots x_n^{i_n},f=i1​,i2​…,in​=0∑∞​ai1​i2​⋯in​​x1i1​​⋯xnin​​,g=i1​,i2​…,in​=0∑∞​bi1​i2​⋯in​​x1i1​​⋯xnin​​,

where ai1i2⋯in,bi1i2⋯ina_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n}, b_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n}ai1​i2​⋯in​​,bi1​i2​⋯in​​ are zero except for only finitely many indices (i1,i2,…,in)\p{i_1, i_2, \ldots, i_n}(i1​,i2​,…,in​), and c∈Fc \in \Fc∈F. Then

f+g≔∑i1,i2…,in=0∞(ai1i2⋯in+bi1i2⋯in)x1i1⋯xnincf≔∑i1,i2…,in=0∞(cai1i2⋯in)x1i1⋯xnin.\begin{aligned} f + g &\coloneqq \sum_{i_1,i_2\ldots,i_n=0}^\infty \p{a_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n} + b_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n}} x_1^{i_1} \cdots x_n^{i_n} \\ cf &\coloneqq \sum_{i_1,i_2\ldots,i_n=0}^\infty \p{ca_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n}} x_1^{i_1} \cdots x_n^{i_n}. \end{aligned}f+gcf​:=i1​,i2​…,in​=0∑∞​(ai1​i2​⋯in​​+bi1​i2​⋯in​​)x1i1​​⋯xnin​​:=i1​,i2​…,in​=0∑∞​(cai1​i2​⋯in​​)x1i1​​⋯xnin​​.​
  1. We just need to check the axioms.

(VS 1) Let f,g∈Vf, g \in Vf,g∈V be as above. Then

f+g=∑i1,i2…,in=0∞(ai1i2⋯in+bi1i2⋯in)x1i1⋯xnin=∑i1,i2…,in=0∞(bi1i2⋯in+ai1i2⋯in)x1i1⋯xnin((F,+) is commutative)=g+f.\begin{aligned} f + g &= \sum_{i_1,i_2\ldots,i_n=0}^\infty \p{a_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n} + b_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n}} x_1^{i_1} \cdots x_n^{i_n} \\ &= \sum_{i_1,i_2\ldots,i_n=0}^\infty \p{b_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n} + a_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n}} x_1^{i_1} \cdots x_n^{i_n} && \p{\p{\F, +} \text{ is commutative}} \\ &= g + f. \end{aligned}f+g​=i1​,i2​…,in​=0∑∞​(ai1​i2​⋯in​​+bi1​i2​⋯in​​)x1i1​​⋯xnin​​=i1​,i2​…,in​=0∑∞​(bi1​i2​⋯in​​+ai1​i2​⋯in​​)x1i1​​⋯xnin​​=g+f.​​((F,+) is commutative)​

(VS 2) Let f,g∈Vf, g \in Vf,g∈V be as above, and let

h=∑i1,i2…,in=0∞ci1i2⋯inx1i1⋯xnin.h = \sum_{i_1,i_2\ldots,i_n=0}^\infty c_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n} x_1^{i_1} \cdots x_n^{i_n}.h=i1​,i2​…,in​=0∑∞​ci1​i2​⋯in​​x1i1​​⋯xnin​​.

Then

(f+g)+h=∑i1,i2…,in=0∞(ai1i2⋯in+bi1i2⋯in)x1i1⋯xnin+∑i1,i2…,in=0∞ci1i2⋯inx1i1⋯xnin=∑i1,i2…,in=0∞((ai1i2⋯in+bi1i2⋯in)+ci1i2⋯in)x1i1⋯xnin=∑i1,i2…,in=0∞(ai1i2⋯in+(bi1i2⋯in+ci1i2⋯in))x1i1⋯xnin((F,+) is associative)=∑i1,i2…,in=0∞ai1i2⋯inx1i1⋯xnin+∑i1,i2…,in=0∞(bi1i2⋯in+ci1i2⋯in)x1i1⋯xnin=f+(g+h).\begin{aligned} \p{f + g} + h &= \sum_{i_1,i_2\ldots,i_n=0}^\infty \p{a_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n} + b_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n}} x_1^{i_1} \cdots x_n^{i_n} + \sum_{i_1,i_2\ldots,i_n=0}^\infty c_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n} x_1^{i_1} \cdots x_n^{i_n} \\ &= \sum_{i_1,i_2\ldots,i_n=0}^\infty \p{\p{a_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n} + b_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n}} + c_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n}} x_1^{i_1} \cdots x_n^{i_n} \\ &= \sum_{i_1,i_2\ldots,i_n=0}^\infty \p{a_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n} + \p{b_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n} + c_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n}}} x_1^{i_1} \cdots x_n^{i_n} && \p{\p{\F, +} \text{ is associative}} \\ &= \sum_{i_1,i_2\ldots,i_n=0}^\infty a_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n} x_1^{i_1} \cdots x_n^{i_n} + \sum_{i_1,i_2\ldots,i_n=0}^\infty \p{b_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n} + c_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n}} x_1^{i_1} \cdots x_n^{i_n} \\ &= f + \p{g + h}. \end{aligned}(f+g)+h​=i1​,i2​…,in​=0∑∞​(ai1​i2​⋯in​​+bi1​i2​⋯in​​)x1i1​​⋯xnin​​+i1​,i2​…,in​=0∑∞​ci1​i2​⋯in​​x1i1​​⋯xnin​​=i1​,i2​…,in​=0∑∞​((ai1​i2​⋯in​​+bi1​i2​⋯in​​)+ci1​i2​⋯in​​)x1i1​​⋯xnin​​=i1​,i2​…,in​=0∑∞​(ai1​i2​⋯in​​+(bi1​i2​⋯in​​+ci1​i2​⋯in​​))x1i1​​⋯xnin​​=i1​,i2​…,in​=0∑∞​ai1​i2​⋯in​​x1i1​​⋯xnin​​+i1​,i2​…,in​=0∑∞​(bi1​i2​⋯in​​+ci1​i2​⋯in​​)x1i1​​⋯xnin​​=f+(g+h).​​((F,+) is associative)​

(VS 3) The zero vector is

0V=∑i1,i2…,in=0∞0Fx1i1⋯xnin.0_V = \sum_{i_1,i_2\ldots,i_n=0}^\infty 0_\F x_1^{i_1} \cdots x_n^{i_n}.0V​=i1​,i2​…,in​=0∑∞​0F​x1i1​​⋯xnin​​.

Indeed, given f∈Vf \in Vf∈V as above,

f+0V=∑i1,i2…,in=0∞(ai1i2⋯in+0F)x1i1⋯xnin=∑i1,i2…,in=0∞ai1i2⋯inx1i1⋯xnin(0F is the additive identity in F)=f.\begin{aligned} f + 0_V &= \sum_{i_1,i_2\ldots,i_n=0}^\infty \p{a_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n} + 0_\F} x_1^{i_1} \cdots x_n^{i_n} \\ &= \sum_{i_1,i_2\ldots,i_n=0}^\infty a_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n} x_1^{i_1} \cdots x_n^{i_n} && \p{0_\F \text{ is the additive identity in }\F} \\ &= f. \end{aligned}f+0V​​=i1​,i2​…,in​=0∑∞​(ai1​i2​⋯in​​+0F​)x1i1​​⋯xnin​​=i1​,i2​…,in​=0∑∞​ai1​i2​⋯in​​x1i1​​⋯xnin​​=f.​​(0F​ is the additive identity in F)​

(VS 4) Given f∈Vf \in Vf∈V as above, note that −ai1i2⋯in∈F-a_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n} \in \F−ai1​i2​⋯in​​∈F since F\FF is a field. Thus, if we set

g=∑i1,i2…,in=0∞(−ai1i2⋯in)x1i1⋯xnin,g = \sum_{i_1,i_2\ldots,i_n=0}^\infty \p{-a_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n}} x_1^{i_1} \cdots x_n^{i_n},g=i1​,i2​…,in​=0∑∞​(−ai1​i2​⋯in​​)x1i1​​⋯xnin​​,

then

f+g=∑i1,i2…,in=0∞(ai1i2⋯in+(−ai1i2⋯in))x1i1⋯xnin=∑i1,i2…,in=0∞0Fx1i1⋯xnin=0V.\begin{aligned} f + g &= \sum_{i_1,i_2\ldots,i_n=0}^\infty \p{a_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n} + \p{-a_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n} }} x_1^{i_1} \cdots x_n^{i_n} \\ &= \sum_{i_1,i_2\ldots,i_n=0}^\infty 0_\F x_1^{i_1} \cdots x_n^{i_n} \\ &= 0_V. \end{aligned}f+g​=i1​,i2​…,in​=0∑∞​(ai1​i2​⋯in​​+(−ai1​i2​⋯in​​))x1i1​​⋯xnin​​=i1​,i2​…,in​=0∑∞​0F​x1i1​​⋯xnin​​=0V​.​

(VS 5) Given f∈Vf \in Vf∈V as above,

1Ff=∑i1,i2…,in=0∞(1Fai1i2⋯in)x1i1⋯xnin=∑i1,i2…,in=0∞ai1i2⋯inx1i1⋯xnin(1F is the multiplicative identity in F)=f.\begin{aligned} 1_\F f &= \sum_{i_1,i_2\ldots,i_n=0}^\infty \p{1_\F a_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n}} x_1^{i_1} \cdots x_n^{i_n} \\ &= \sum_{i_1,i_2\ldots,i_n=0}^\infty a_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n} x_1^{i_1} \cdots x_n^{i_n} && \p{1_\F \text{ is the multiplicative identity in }\F} \\ &= f. \end{aligned}1F​f​=i1​,i2​…,in​=0∑∞​(1F​ai1​i2​⋯in​​)x1i1​​⋯xnin​​=i1​,i2​…,in​=0∑∞​ai1​i2​⋯in​​x1i1​​⋯xnin​​=f.​​(1F​ is the multiplicative identity in F)​

(VS 6) Let f∈Vf \in Vf∈V be as above, and b,c∈Fb, c \in \Fb,c∈F. Then

(bc)f=∑i1,i2…,in=0∞((bc)ai1i2⋯in)x1i1⋯xnin=∑i1,i2…,in=0∞(b(cai1i2⋯in))x1i1⋯xnin((F, ⋅ ) is associative)=b∑i1,i2…,in=0∞(cai1i2⋯in)x1i1⋯xnin=b(cf).\begin{aligned} \p{bc}f &= \sum_{i_1,i_2\ldots,i_n=0}^\infty \p{\p{bc} a_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n}} x_1^{i_1} \cdots x_n^{i_n} \\ &= \sum_{i_1,i_2\ldots,i_n=0}^\infty \p{b \p{ca_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n}}} x_1^{i_1} \cdots x_n^{i_n} && \p{\p{\F, \,\cdot\,} \text{ is associative}} \\ &= b \sum_{i_1,i_2\ldots,i_n=0}^\infty \p{ca_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n}} x_1^{i_1} \cdots x_n^{i_n} \\ &= b\p{cf}. \end{aligned}(bc)f​=i1​,i2​…,in​=0∑∞​((bc)ai1​i2​⋯in​​)x1i1​​⋯xnin​​=i1​,i2​…,in​=0∑∞​(b(cai1​i2​⋯in​​))x1i1​​⋯xnin​​=bi1​,i2​…,in​=0∑∞​(cai1​i2​⋯in​​)x1i1​​⋯xnin​​=b(cf).​​((F,⋅) is associative)​

(VS 7) Let f,g∈Vf, g \in Vf,g∈V be as above and c∈Fc \in \Fc∈F. Then

c(f+g)=c∑i1,i2…,in=0∞(ai1i2⋯in+bi1i2⋯in)x1i1⋯xnin=∑i1,i2…,in=0∞(c(ai1i2⋯in+bi1i2⋯in))x1i1⋯xnin=∑i1,i2…,in=0∞(cai1i2⋯in+cbi1i2⋯in)x1i1⋯xnin((F,+, ⋅ ) is distributive)=∑i1,i2…,in=0∞(cai1i2⋯in)x1i1⋯xnin+∑i1,i2…,in=0∞(cbi1i2⋯in)x1i1⋯xnin=cf+cg.\begin{aligned} c\p{f + g} &= c\sum_{i_1,i_2\ldots,i_n=0}^\infty \p{a_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n} + b_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n}} x_1^{i_1} \cdots x_n^{i_n} \\ &= \sum_{i_1,i_2\ldots,i_n=0}^\infty \p{c\p{a_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n} + b_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n}}} x_1^{i_1} \cdots x_n^{i_n} \\ &= \sum_{i_1,i_2\ldots,i_n=0}^\infty \p{ca_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n} + cb_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n}} x_1^{i_1} \cdots x_n^{i_n} && \p{\p{\F, +, \,\cdot\,}\text{ is distributive}} \\ &= \sum_{i_1,i_2\ldots,i_n=0}^\infty \p{ca_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n}} x_1^{i_1} \cdots x_n^{i_n} + \sum_{i_1,i_2\ldots,i_n=0}^\infty \p{cb_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n}} x_1^{i_1} \cdots x_n^{i_n} \\ &= cf + cg. \end{aligned}c(f+g)​=ci1​,i2​…,in​=0∑∞​(ai1​i2​⋯in​​+bi1​i2​⋯in​​)x1i1​​⋯xnin​​=i1​,i2​…,in​=0∑∞​(c(ai1​i2​⋯in​​+bi1​i2​⋯in​​))x1i1​​⋯xnin​​=i1​,i2​…,in​=0∑∞​(cai1​i2​⋯in​​+cbi1​i2​⋯in​​)x1i1​​⋯xnin​​=i1​,i2​…,in​=0∑∞​(cai1​i2​⋯in​​)x1i1​​⋯xnin​​+i1​,i2​…,in​=0∑∞​(cbi1​i2​⋯in​​)x1i1​​⋯xnin​​=cf+cg.​​((F,+,⋅) is distributive)​

(VS 8) Let f∈Vf \in Vf∈V be as above and b,c∈Fb, c \in \Fb,c∈F. Then

(b+c)f=∑i1,i2…,in=0∞((b+c)ai1i2⋯in)x1i1⋯xnin=∑i1,i2…,in=0∞(bai1i2⋯in+cai1i2⋯in)x1i1⋯xnin((F,+, ⋅ ) is distributive)=∑i1,i2…,in=0∞(bai1i2⋯in)x1i1⋯xnin+∑i1,i2…,in=0∞(cai1i2⋯in)x1i1⋯xnin=bf+cf.\begin{aligned} \p{b + c}f &= \sum_{i_1,i_2\ldots,i_n=0}^\infty \p{\p{b + c}a_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n}} x_1^{i_1} \cdots x_n^{i_n} \\ &= \sum_{i_1,i_2\ldots,i_n=0}^\infty \p{ba_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n} + ca_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n}} x_1^{i_1} \cdots x_n^{i_n} && \p{\p{\F, +, \,\cdot\,}\text{ is distributive}} \\ &= \sum_{i_1,i_2\ldots,i_n=0}^\infty \p{ba_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n}} x_1^{i_1} \cdots x_n^{i_n} + \sum_{i_1,i_2\ldots,i_n=0}^\infty \p{ca_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n}} x_1^{i_1} \cdots x_n^{i_n} \\ &= bf + cf. \end{aligned}(b+c)f​=i1​,i2​…,in​=0∑∞​((b+c)ai1​i2​⋯in​​)x1i1​​⋯xnin​​=i1​,i2​…,in​=0∑∞​(bai1​i2​⋯in​​+cai1​i2​⋯in​​)x1i1​​⋯xnin​​=i1​,i2​…,in​=0∑∞​(bai1​i2​⋯in​​)x1i1​​⋯xnin​​+i1​,i2​…,in​=0∑∞​(cai1​i2​⋯in​​)x1i1​​⋯xnin​​=bf+cf.​​((F,+,⋅) is distributive)​

  1. There are three things to check. Let f,g∈Vf, g \in Vf,g∈V be as above, c∈Fc \in \Fc∈F, and we further assume that f,gf, gf,g are homogeneous. Then 0V0_V0V​ is homogeneous of degree kkk vacuously (there are no non-zero terms to check the condition on).

    Next, let's show that f+gf + gf+g are homogeneous of degree kkk. Recall that

    f+g=∑i1,i2…,in=0∞(ai1i2⋯in+bi1i2⋯in)x1i1⋯xnin.f + g = \sum_{i_1,i_2\ldots,i_n=0}^\infty \p{a_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n} + b_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n}} x_1^{i_1} \cdots x_n^{i_n}.f+g=i1​,i2​…,in​=0∑∞​(ai1​i2​⋯in​​+bi1​i2​⋯in​​)x1i1​​⋯xnin​​.

    We need to show that if (ai1i2⋯in+bi1i2⋯in)x1i1⋯xnin\p{a_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n} + b_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n}} x_1^{i_1} \cdots x_n^{i_n}(ai1​i2​⋯in​​+bi1​i2​⋯in​​)x1i1​​⋯xnin​​ is a non-zero term, then i1+i2+⋯+in=ki_1 + i_2 + \cdots + i_n = ki1​+i2​+⋯+in​=k. Assume this term is non-zero, which means that ai1i2⋯in+bi1i2⋯in≠0a_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n} + b_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n} \neq 0ai1​i2​⋯in​​+bi1​i2​⋯in​​=0. Thus, at least one of ai1i2⋯ina_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n}ai1​i2​⋯in​​ and bi1i2⋯inb_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n}bi1​i2​⋯in​​ is non-zero. Without loss of generality, we assume that ai1i2⋯in≠0a_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n} \neq 0ai1​i2​⋯in​​=0. Otherwise, we can replace ai1i2⋯ina_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n}ai1​i2​⋯in​​ with bi1i2⋯inb_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n}bi1​i2​⋯in​​ in the following proof.

    Since ai1i2⋯in≠0a_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n} \neq 0ai1​i2​⋯in​​=0, we know that ai1i2⋯inx1i1⋯xnina_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n} x_1^{i_1} \cdots x_n^{i_n}ai1​i2​⋯in​​x1i1​​⋯xnin​​ is a non-zero term of fff. But fff is homogeneous of degree kkk, so by definition, i1+i2+⋯+in=ki_1 + i_2 + \cdots + i_n = ki1​+i2​+⋯+in​=k. This shows that f+gf + gf+g is homogeneous of degree kkk.

    Lastly, we need to show that cfcfcf is homogeneous of degree kkk. If c=0c = 0c=0, then cf=0cf = 0cf=0, which we already know is homogeneous of degree kkk. Otherwise, suppose (cai1i2⋯in)x1i1⋯xnin\p{ca_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n}}x_1^{i_1} \cdots x_n^{i_n}(cai1​i2​⋯in​​)x1i1​​⋯xnin​​ is a non-zero term of cfcfcf. Then because c≠0c \neq 0c=0, we know that ai1i2⋯in≠0a_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n} \neq 0ai1​i2​⋯in​​=0. Thus, ai1i2⋯inx1i1⋯xnina_{i_1 i_2 \cdots i_n} x_1^{i_1} \cdots x_n^{i_n}ai1​i2​⋯in​​x1i1​​⋯xnin​​ is a non-zero term of fff, so by degree-kkk homogeneity of fff, we have i1+i2+⋯+in=ki_1 + i_2 + \cdots + i_n = ki1​+i2​+⋯+in​=k, so cfcfcf is homogeneous of degree kkk.

  2. Let f,g∈Vf, g \in Vf,g∈V be symmetric and let c∈Fc \in \Fc∈F. Note that 0F0_\F0F​ is symmetric since all its terms are zero, so after exchanging any two variables, all the terms will still remain zero. Next,

Problem 5

but these are different since 2≠122 \neq \frac{1}{2}2=21​.
